{"title_page": "Richard Louis Hunter", "text_new": "{{short description|American forger and serial killer}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name        = Richard Louis Hunter\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| alt         = \n| birth_name  = \n| alias       = \n| birth_date  = 1955\n| birth_place = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| cause       = \n| conviction  = [[Murder]] x4<br>Rape x4<br>Burglary x4<br>[[Forgery]] x1\n| sentence    = [[Life imprisonment]]\n| victims     = 4\n| beginyear   = March\n| endyear     = April 1986\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| states      = [[Georgia (state)|Georgia]]\n| apprehended = April 20, 1986\n| imprisoned  = \n}}\n'''Richard Louis Hunter'''<ref group=n>Middle name is spelled 'Lewis'</ref> (born 1955) is a convicted [[United States|American]] [[serial killer]] and forger. A day laborer, Hunter raped and killed four elderly women in [[Atlanta]] between March and April 1986, robbing their apartments afterwards. He later plead guilty to the murders and numerous robberies, and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]].<ref name=term>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41657911/hunter-pleads-guilty-1/|title=Man gets 8 life terms in stranglings|author=Gary Hendricks|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 6, 1987}}</ref>\n\n==Murders==\nThe first victim was 85-year-old Annie Rochelle Copeland, who lived alone in a small apartment in southwest Atlanta. She was found by a neighbor, a [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]], on March 1, 1986, who got worried after knocking on the door and receiving no reply. She was found lying on her bed in the fetal position, covered with a bedspread and blanket, and her face covered by a pillow and her blue nightgown. The apartment had been turned upside down, with items from a pocketbook strewn about and a bloody pillowcase placed between her legs. The perpetrator had managed to enter by cutting the screen of a living room window and pulling out the windowpane.<ref name=sly>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653775/richard-lewis-hunter-victims-and-early/|title=Slayings|author=Bill Montgomery|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 12, 1986}}</ref> The killing scared other elderly residents living near [[Clark University]], who took additional measures to protect themselves in case the perpetrator struck again.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41652736/annie-rochelle-copeland-richard-hunter/|title=Police believe robbery motive in women's killing|author=David Corvette|publisher=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=March 2, 1986}}</ref>\n\nOnly a few days later, on March 6, 25-year-old Felton Clements went to check on his 61-year-old mother Aretha, who lived alone in northwest Atlanta, only to find her dead and her apartment ransacked. Mrs. Clements had been manually strangled and then wrapped up in her bedspread, nightgown disarranged, her head put against the foot of the bed and her right leg beneath her. Her plants had been overturned, her drawers emptied, with the killer then stealing her 25-inch color TV set and a pocketbook.<ref name=sly/> There were no suspects in this case either, as Aretha rarely left her home, except when visiting her best friend or for treatment at [[Grady Memorial Hospital]].<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41652957/aretha-clements-hunter-victim/|title=Son finds mother, 61, slain at her small apartment|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 7, 1986}}</ref>\n\nThe situation repeated on March 11, with the discovery of the body of 62-year-old Dena Mae Mike, a blind woman who hasn't been seen in two days.<ref name=hunt>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653182/dena-mae-mike-pt1-hunter/|title=Police hunt link in slayings of 3 elderly women|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 12, 1986}}</ref> Similarly to Copeland and Clements, she had either been smothered, and several objects had been placed on her head, including a sweater, a pillow, a plastic garment bag with clothing on hangers and a duffel bag. Like Copeland, her nightgown had been trampled with, and a bloody pillowcase was found between her legs.<ref name=sly/> Her killer had apparently entered through a kitchen window.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653225/dena-mike-murder-by-hunter-pt2/|title=Slayings|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 12, 1986}}</ref> With Mike's death, law enforcement from Atlanta Homicide began to make connections between the recent murders: all of the victims had been elderly black women, living alone off [[Social Security (United States)|social security benefits]], within one general area, and all had had their apartments burgled and items stolen after death. The [[Georgia Bureau of Investigation|GBI]] was involved in the investigations, and residents of the area were querried about any suspicious individuals in the area.<ref name=hunt/>\n\nFor the following weeks, the murders suddenly ceased, before abruptly resuming with the killing of 65-year-old Grace Hill on April 9. She was found by her friends, partially naked, on her living room floor in northwest Atlanta, suffocated to death and signs of possible sexual assault. The killer, whom had entered through an unlocked back door, had put a newspaper over her chest, and a doll between her legs.<ref name=sly/> With her death, the authorities officially announced to the media that they were investigating all four deaths as the doings of a serial killer.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653358/grace-hill-4th-victim-of-hunter/|title=Fourth elderly women found dead|publisher=[[Hawaii Tribune-Herald]]|date=April 10, 1986}}</ref>\n\n===Community response and perpetrator profile===\nThe murders caused a great stir in the city, including among politicians and community leaders, with then-Governor [[Joe Frank Harris]] offering a total of $8,000 reward for any information regarding the murders. Comparisons were also drawn to the [[Atlanta murders of 1979\u20131981]], albeit most of the victims were younger males.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653503/richard-hunter-victim-similarities/|title=Elderly westside victims lived, died in poverty and isolation|author=Bill Montgomery|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 12, 1986}}</ref> According to Dr. James Alan Fox, the killer was black, in his 30s, and lived near the victims, additionally theorizing that he was a sadist and that he might've developed a hatred for the elderly due to an abusive childhood.<ref name=sly/>\n\n==Arrest, trial and imprisonment==\nIn mid-April, an anonymous tip was received by police about a certain felon who should be investigated for the series. On April 20, the authorities arrested that suspect, who was residing in his girlfriend's house with their four children, on a probation violation - a 31-year-old convicted forger named Richard Louis Hunter, who had lived in the neighborhood.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654074/richard-lewis-hunter-arrested/|title=Suspect Arrested in Slayings of Elderly|publisher=[[Pharos-Tribune]]|date=April 24, 1986}}</ref><ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41657988/hunter-pleads-2/|title=Man gets 8 life terms in stranglings, page 2|author=Gary Hendricks|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 6, 1987}}</ref> Hunter was quickly ordered to undergo psychological tests at Grady Memorial Hospital, and was arraigned for court on May 8.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654182/hunter-to-be-psych-tested/|title=Accused killer must undergo tests|publisher=The Daily Spectrum|date=April 24, 1986}}</ref> On May 10, he was charged with the murder while sitting in the Atlanta city jail.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654342/richard-hunter-indicted-for-4-slayings/|title=Hunter is indicted in all four slayings of elderly black women|author=James Alexander Jr.|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 10, 1986}}</ref> Although officials deterred from saying how strong there was evidence against Hunter was, one anonymous source claimed that they had strong fingerprints matching those of the accused, who had already admitted to attempting to sell Copeland's TV set, but also claimed to have had an accomplice.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654374/hunter-indicted-for-4-murders/|title=Hunter|author=James Alexander Jr.|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 10, 1986}}</ref> Eventually, in order to avoid the [[death penalty]], Hunter plead guilty to the murders, and received 8 life sentences, plus 80 years for the burglaries associated with the killings. According to District Attorney Lewis R. Slaton, he would have to serve at least 30 years before being eligible for parole.<ref name=term/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Atlanta murders of 1979\u20131981]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://serialdispatches.com/hunter-richard-lewis/ Serial Dispatches article]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Richard Louis}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of rape]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:People convicted of burglary]]\n[[Category:People convicted of forgery]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:People from Atlanta]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American forger and serial killer}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name        = Richard Louis Hunter\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| alt         = \n| birth_name  = \n| alias       = \n| birth_date  = 1955\n| birth_place = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| cause       = \n| conviction  = [[Murder]] x4<br>Rape x4<br>Burglary x4<br>[[Forgery]] x1\n| sentence    = [[Life imprisonment]]\n| victims     = 4\n| beginyear   = March\n| endyear     = April 1986\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| states      = [[Georgia (state)|Georgia]]\n| apprehended = April 20, 1986\n| imprisoned  = \n}}\n'''Richard Louis Hunter'''<ref group=n> Middle name is spelled 'Lewis'</ref> (born 1955) is a convicted [[United States|American]] [[serial killer]] and forger. A day laborer, Hunter raped and killed four elderly women in [[Atlanta]] between March and April 1986, robbing their apartments afterwards. He later plead guilty to the murders and numerous robberies, and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]].<ref name=term>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41657911/hunter-pleads-guilty-1/|title=Man gets 8 life terms in stranglings|author=Gary Hendricks|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 6, 1987}}</ref>\n==Murders==\nThe first victim was 85-year-old Annie Rochelle Copeland, who lived alone in a small apartment in southwest Atlanta. She was found by a neighbor, a [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]], on March 1, 1986, who got worried after knocking on the door and receiving no reply. She was found lying on her bed in the fetal position, covered with a bedspread and blanket, and her face covered by a pillow and her blue nightgown. The apartment had been turned upside down, with items from a pocketbook strewn about and a bloody pillowcase placed between her legs. The perpetrator had managed to enter by cutting the screen of a living room window and pulling out the windowpane.<ref name=sly>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653775/richard-lewis-hunter-victims-and-early/|title=Slayings|author=Bill Montgomery|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 12, 1986}}</ref> The killing scared other elderly residents living near [[Clark University]], who took additional measures to protect themselves in case the perpetrator struck again.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41652736/annie-rochelle-copeland-richard-hunter/|title=Police believe robbery motive in women's killing|author=David Corvette|publisher=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=March 2, 1986}}</ref>\n\nOnly a few days later, on March 6th, 25-year-old Felton Clements went to check on his 61-year-old mother Aretha, who lived alone in northwest Atlanta, only to find her dead and her apartment ransacked. Mrs. Clements had been manually strangled and then wrapped up in her bedspread, nightgown disarranged, her head put against the foot of the bed and her right leg beneath her. Her plants had been overturned, her drawers emptied, with the killer then stealing her 25-inch color TV set and a pocketbook.<ref name=sly/> There were no suspects in this case either, as Aretha rarely left her home, except when visiting her best friend or for treatment at [[Grady Memorial Hospital]].<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41652957/aretha-clements-hunter-victim/|title=Son finds mother, 61, slain at her small apartment|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 7, 1986}}</ref>\n\nThe situation repeated on March 11th, with the discovery of the body of 62-year-old Dena Mae Mike, a blind woman who hasn't been seen in two days.<ref name=hunt>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653182/dena-mae-mike-pt1-hunter/|title=Police hunt link in slayings of 3 elderly women|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 12, 1986}}</ref> Similarly to Copeland and Clements, she had either been smothered, and several objects had been placed on her head, including a sweater, a pillow, a plastic garment bag with clothing on hangers and a duffel bag. Like Copeland, her nightgown had been trampled with, and a bloody pillowcase was found between her legs.<ref name=sly/> Her killer had apparently entered through a kitchen window.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653225/dena-mike-murder-by-hunter-pt2/|title=Slayings|author=Larry Copeland|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=March 12, 1986}}</ref> With Mike's death, law enforcement from Atlanta Homicide began to make connections between the recent murders: all of the victims had been elderly black women, living alone off [[Social Security (United States)|social security benefits]], within one general area, and all had had their apartments burgled and items stolen after death. The [[Georgia Bureau of Investigation|GBI]] was involved in the investigations, and residents of the area were querried about any suspicious individuals in the area.<ref name=hunt/>\n\nFor the following weeks, the murders suddenly ceased, before abruptly resuming with the killing of 65-year-old Grace Hill on April 9th. She was found by her friends, partially naked, on her living room floor in northwest Atlanta, suffocated to death and signs of possible sexual assault. The killer, whom had entered through an unlocked back door, had put a newspaper over her chest, and a doll between her legs.<ref name=sly/> With her death, the authorities officially announced to the media that they were investigating all four deaths as the doings of a serial killer.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653358/grace-hill-4th-victim-of-hunter/|title=Fourth elderly women found dead|publisher=[[Hawaii Tribune-Herald]]|date=April 10, 1986}}</ref>\n===Community response and perpetrator profile===\nThe murders caused a great stir in the city, including among politicians and community leaders, with then-Governor [[Joe Frank Harris]] offering a total of $8,000 reward for any information regarding the murders. Comparisons were also drawn to the [[Atlanta murders of 1979\u20131981]], albeit most of the victims were younger males.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41653503/richard-hunter-victim-similarities/|title=Elderly westside victims lived, died in poverty and isolation|author=Bill Montgomery|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 12, 1986}}</ref> According to Dr. James Alan Fox, the killer was black, in his 30s, and lived near the victims, additionally theorizing that he was a sadist and that he might've developed a hatred for the elderly due to an abusive childhood.<ref name=sly/>\n==Arrest, trial and imprisonment==\nIn mid-April, an anonymous tip was received by police about a certain felon who should be investigated for the series. On April 20th, the authorities arrested that suspect, who was residing in his girlfriend's house with their four children, on a probation violation - a 31-year-old convicted forger named Richard Louis Hunter, who had lived in the neighborhood.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654074/richard-lewis-hunter-arrested/|title=Suspect Arrested in Slayings of Elderly|publisher=[[Pharos-Tribune]]|date=April 24, 1986}}</ref><ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41657988/hunter-pleads-2/|title=Man gets 8 life terms in stranglings, page 2|author=Gary Hendricks|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 6, 1987}}</ref> Hunter was quickly ordered to undergo psychological tests at Grady Memorial Hospital, and was arraigned for court on May 8th.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654182/hunter-to-be-psych-tested/|title=Accused killer must undergo tests|publisher=The Daily Spectrum|date=April 24, 1986}}</ref> On May 10th, he was charged with the murder while sitting in the Atlanta city jail.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654342/richard-hunter-indicted-for-4-slayings/|title=Hunter is indicted in all four slayings of elderly black women|author=James Alexander Jr.|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 10, 1986}}</ref> Although officials deterred from saying how strong their was evidence against Hunter was, one anonymous source claimed that they had strong fingerprints matching those of the accused, who had already admitted to attempting to sell Copeland's TV set, but also claimed to have had an accomplice.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41654374/hunter-indicted-for-4-murders/|title=Hunter|author=James Alexander Jr.|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 10, 1986}}</ref> Eventually, in order to avoid the [[death penalty]], Hunter plead guilty to the murders, and received 8 life sentences, plus 80 years for the burglaries associated with the killings. According to District Attorney Lewis R. Slaton, he would have to serve at least 30 years before being eligible for parole.<ref name=term/>\n==See also==\n* [[Atlanta murders of 1979\u20131981]]\n==External links==\n* [https://serialdispatches.com/hunter-richard-lewis/ Serial Dispatches article]\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Richard Louis}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of rape]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:People convicted of burglary]]\n[[Category:People convicted of forgery]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:People from Atlanta]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: their was \u2192 there was", "